00:04:34.220 --> 00:04:36.860
And I've focused particularly
on the period

00:04:36.860 --> 00:04:38.160
because I couldn't do everything.

00:04:38.160 --> 00:04:43.850
I decided to simply deep-dive into
the period, 1914 to about 1918,

00:04:43.850 --> 00:04:45.970
which coincided with
the war, of course,

00:04:45.970 --> 00:04:49.400
but I was not really concerned
to relate it directly to the war.

00:04:49.400 --> 00:04:51.200
We can talk about that if
you want because I know many

00:04:51.200 --> 00:04:54.590
of you are interested in that
period and its relationship--

00:04:54.590 --> 00:04:57.770
the relationship of the
war to culture at the time.

00:04:57.770 --> 00:04:59.070
So let me start.

00:04:59.070 --> 00:05:00.370
Let's take a case.

00:05:00.370 --> 00:05:01.670
Let's take a case.

00:05:01.670 --> 00:05:06.060
How are you going to show on
film face-to-face encounters,

00:05:06.060 --> 00:05:07.980
two people having a
conversation was one another?

00:05:07.980 --> 00:05:09.280
Well, here's an example.

00:05:09.280 --> 00:05:12.370
From Hidden Figures, a recent
film you might have seen,

00:05:12.370 --> 00:05:16.860
where the computer, as she's
called, faces off against the boss

00:05:16.860 --> 00:05:19.480
of the NASA agency
she's working for.

00:05:19.480 --> 00:05:21.960
And instead of playing out
that scene in the entirety

00:05:21.960 --> 00:05:27.220
of that long two-shot, we
get a cut to her speaking--

00:05:27.220 --> 00:05:30.730
explaining why she takes
so long-- such long breaks.

00:05:30.730 --> 00:05:34.260
And then, we have another cut
to him looking at her answering

00:05:34.260 --> 00:05:36.370
and speaking to her, asking
her further questions,

00:05:36.370 --> 00:05:39.480
and then we have a
shot of her again.

00:05:39.480 --> 00:05:40.930
And I'd point out to
you that the shot

00:05:40.930 --> 00:05:42.500
of her isn't the same
one we had before.

00:05:42.500 --> 00:05:45.760
It's a different framing
or much closer to her.

00:05:45.760 --> 00:05:47.410
Now, this may seem no news.

00:05:47.410 --> 00:05:48.710
This seems very natural.

00:05:48.710 --> 00:05:52.370
In fact, you might ask, how else
would you film a face-to-face

00:05:52.370 --> 00:05:56.200
encounter except by setting it up
and then singling out each person

00:05:56.200 --> 00:05:59.040
in turn as they take
turns in the conversation?

00:05:59.040 --> 00:06:00.340
Well, it goes back.

00:06:00.340 --> 00:06:05.690
We go back to hundred years from
2016 to 1916, Reginald Barker,

00:06:05.690 --> 00:06:07.570
the man you saw at the
beginning in my first slide,

00:06:07.570 --> 00:06:09.140
handled it much the same way.

00:06:09.140 --> 00:06:12.080
We have our master shot, not
in the wide screen like we have

00:06:12.080 --> 00:06:14.870
with Hidden Figures, but that's
a more recent development.

00:06:14.870 --> 00:06:17.520
Master shot of the two people
engaged in conversation,

00:06:17.520 --> 00:06:23.950 position:56%
more than a conversation, a cut to
her reacting, a cut to him reacting.

00:06:23.950 --> 00:06:27.710
And then another shot of
her, closer, just as we had

00:06:27.710 --> 00:06:29.010
in Hidden Figures,

00:06:29.010 --> 00:06:32.550
sort of intensifying our
attention on her reaction.

00:06:32.550 --> 00:06:34.080
So, you think again.

00:06:34.080 --> 00:06:36.890
So what, how else would
you film a conversation?

00:06:36.890 --> 00:06:39.920
Well, it turns out that if
you assume cinema is invented

00:06:39.920 --> 00:06:43.950
around 1895, it takes
about 20 years for people

00:06:43.950 --> 00:06:45.460
to figure out how to do this.

00:06:45.460 --> 00:06:48.040 position:56%
It would seem to be the most natural
spontaneous thing in the world.

00:06:48.040 --> 00:06:50.410
And yet, it takes a
long time for filmmakers

00:06:50.410 --> 00:06:52.590
to adopt this particular manner

00:06:52.590 --> 00:06:55.270
of representing these
face-to-face encounters.

00:06:55.270 --> 00:06:59.050
Before that, things were shot
very differently, long shots,

00:06:59.050 --> 00:07:02.410
distant shots, long-held
shots as in The Passion

00:07:02.410 --> 00:07:04.490
of the Christ, the
early Lumiere film.

00:07:04.490 --> 00:07:07.950
And then 10 years later,
Accidents Will Happen.

00:07:07.950 --> 00:07:13.070
You see it's very flat,
very distant and no cutting.

00:07:14.130 --> 00:07:18.010
Filmmakers start in the [inaudible]
to mount more complicated scenes

00:07:18.010 --> 00:07:23.070
than the examples I'd just given
you, but they don't use editing.

00:07:23.070 --> 00:07:26.030
Now, one of the points of
using that example of the--

00:07:26.030 --> 00:07:29.390
of Hidden Figures and
Vain Desires is

00:07:29.390 --> 00:07:31.710
that it guides your
attention, doesn't it?

00:07:31.710 --> 00:07:35.690
Those shots, those cuts point you
to what's important in the scene.

00:07:35.690 --> 00:07:39.240
But a scene like Ready Money or
the scene of The Sign of the Cross,

00:07:39.240 --> 00:07:41.590
it just seems to be
dumping everything in.

00:07:41.590 --> 00:07:43.690
It seems to be a kind of mess.

00:07:43.690 --> 00:07:48.070
So the question is, what would
make anyone think that this,

00:07:48.070 --> 00:07:51.350
for 20 years, is preferable
to this cleaner,

00:07:51.350 --> 00:07:54.110
neater more efficiently
way of lining things up.

00:07:54.110 --> 00:07:55.410
So, my tasks today are these.

00:07:55.410 --> 00:07:58.290
I want to sketch the filmmaking
context of that period,

00:07:58.290 --> 00:08:01.190
to suggest the circumstances
that would lead to people,

00:08:01.190 --> 00:08:04.420
intelligent people like ourselves,
to make that kind of choice.

00:08:04.420 --> 00:08:08.330
I'd like to consider how the
trend toward editing got going.

00:08:08.330 --> 00:08:11.930
And then I'll try to
consider an alternative style

00:08:11.930 --> 00:08:14.310
which actually was the
loser in that battle.

00:08:14.310 --> 00:08:17.250
And then I'll sketch some
causes very briefly at the end,

00:08:17.250 --> 00:08:19.680
some causes for the
developments that we see.

00:08:19.680 --> 00:08:22.520
So let me start with
the period, the context.

00:08:22.520 --> 00:08:24.760
This is an important period,
as I said at the outset,

00:08:24.760 --> 00:08:29.350
because it's really the emergence
of many dimensions of filmmaking.

00:08:29.350 --> 00:08:32.010
First, the business of
film, film industries.

00:08:32.010 --> 00:08:35.860
You start to get the consolidation
of the international film business

00:08:35.860 --> 00:08:40.230
around World War I, the
creation or revamping or decline

00:08:40.230 --> 00:08:45.190 position:56%
of major European firms like Nordisk
in Denmark, Film d' art in France,

00:08:45.190 --> 00:08:47.900
Svensk Filmindustri of Sweden.

00:08:47.900 --> 00:08:50.460
And especially important
for our purposes is the fact

00:08:50.460 --> 00:08:53.010
that at this point, we
start to see the birth

00:08:53.010 --> 00:08:54.600
of Hollywood in that period.

00:08:54.600 --> 00:08:59.300 position:56%
The major studios which are still
with us today, Loew's or Metro, Fox,

00:08:59.300 --> 00:09:01.680
Paramount, Universal,
Goldwyn, United Artists,

00:09:01.680 --> 00:09:05.010
and the very tailend
around 1920, Columbia.

00:09:05.010 --> 00:09:08.640
All these studios are really
started in one form or another,

00:09:08.640 --> 00:09:13.650
sometimes pretty crude as business
enterprises in this period.

00:09:13.650 --> 00:09:17.340
So the market film industry
is about 100 years old.

00:09:17.340 --> 00:09:19.690 position:56%
We also had many important artists--

00:09:19.690 --> 00:09:22.390
film artists working in
those industries, Urban Gad,

00:09:22.390 --> 00:09:25.460
Gallone in Italy, Feuillade,
Gance, Griffith,

00:09:25.460 --> 00:09:27.500 position:56%
of course everybody knows that name.

00:09:27.500 --> 00:09:30.000
Mack Sennett, Cecil B.
DeMille, Thomas Ince,

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:32.200
Charlie Chaplin, again,
very familiar.

00:09:32.200 --> 00:09:35.570
These are the people whose
careers start in that window.

00:09:35.570 --> 00:09:38.780
At the same time, the
industry is starting

00:09:38.780 --> 00:09:42.620
to show us what movies
can be like in exhibition.

00:09:42.620 --> 00:09:45.380
We had the emergence of what we
might call our movie theatres.

00:09:45.380 --> 00:09:48.780
Early on, legitimate theatres were
converted for film screenings.

00:09:48.780 --> 00:09:53.990 position:56%
This is after the period before 1908
where films are shown in carnivals,

00:09:53.990 --> 00:09:57.540
in small storefronts, so-called
Nickelodeons and so on.

00:09:57.540 --> 00:10:00.480
But around this period of
1908, we have purpose-built--

00:10:00.480 --> 00:10:03.120
or purpose-rebuilt film theatres.

00:10:03.120 --> 00:10:06.010
And especially with the
rise of the feature film.

00:10:06.010 --> 00:10:07.570
The feature film was
a film initially

00:10:07.570 --> 00:10:08.870
that simply could be featured.

00:10:08.870 --> 00:10:11.780
You could advertise it that
people would come by name rather

00:10:11.780 --> 00:10:13.640
than simply treating
it like YouTube.

00:10:13.640 --> 00:10:14.940
You just turn it on and what--

00:10:14.940 --> 00:10:16.980
you walk in or whatever
is playing is playing.

00:10:16.980 --> 00:10:18.280
A feature film is originally
just one

00:10:18.280 --> 00:10:20.180
that could be advertised by title.

00:10:20.180 --> 00:10:22.710
But later, this so-called feature
film was as we know it today,

00:10:22.710 --> 00:10:26.740
is a long movie, is a separate
long movie as opposed to a short.

00:10:26.740 --> 00:10:28.040
The length might vary.

00:10:28.040 --> 00:10:30.890
It might be a two-reeler, a
three-reeler, or a four-reeler

00:10:30.890 --> 00:10:34.040
and gets standardized around the
mid themes at about five reels

00:10:34.040 --> 00:10:35.980
or about an hour and
10 minutes or so.

00:10:35.980 --> 00:10:38.470
Seven minute though, but that
could be a little bit less.

00:10:38.470 --> 00:10:41.580
So the feature comes in, and
that reinforces the growth

00:10:41.580 --> 00:10:44.570
of these movie theaters, these
purpose-built movie houses.

00:10:44.570 --> 00:10:46.070
So let's go to Wisconsin
for a while.

00:10:46.070 --> 00:10:48.770
I don't recommend it all the
time, but let's do it now.

00:10:48.770 --> 00:10:51.950
Let's go with the Baraboo,
Wisconsin, 1916.

00:10:51.950 --> 00:10:54.380
If you went to see a movie
in Baraboo, Wisconsin,

00:10:54.380 --> 00:10:57.700
you go to the Gem Theatre
and it's a movie house.

00:10:57.700 --> 00:11:00.990 position:56%
It's not that different from a movie
house in the town you grew up in.

00:11:00.990 --> 00:11:03.810
It's rather different from a
multiplex as they are today,

00:11:03.810 --> 00:11:06.320
but a single screen
theatre, you go in,

00:11:06.320 --> 00:11:09.780
you pay your money,
you watch a few movies.

00:11:09.780 --> 00:11:12.080
More elaborately, still
in Wisconsin,

00:11:12.080 --> 00:11:16.230
and this is why I really do
wish for a time machine, 1916,

00:11:16.230 --> 00:11:18.280
the Butterfly Theatre in Milwaukee.

00:11:18.280 --> 00:11:20.600
This is one gorgeous look
in movie theatre, isn't it?

00:11:20.600 --> 00:11:23.560
This is not even yet
a picture palace.

00:11:23.560 --> 00:11:26.900
There isn't that huge inside, but
it's magnificent on the outside.

00:11:26.900 --> 00:11:29.550
I'd go there today if I
could, no more, of course.

00:11:29.550 --> 00:11:32.960
But this gives you a sense of the
scale of the American film industry

00:11:32.960 --> 00:11:36.140
at this period, with--
exhibitors can actually invest

00:11:36.140 --> 00:11:37.490
in a venue like this.

00:11:37.490 --> 00:11:40.540
OK, not just in Wisconsin, the
American Cosmograph Theatre

00:11:40.540 --> 00:11:43.460
in Cairo is a very
impressive theatre.

00:11:43.460 --> 00:11:46.020
And, of course, the Palads
Teatret, which is about the size

00:11:46.020 --> 00:11:49.900
