00:13:17.970 --> 00:13:21.220
William S. Hart, Mary Pickford,
and so on and so forth.

00:13:21.220 --> 00:13:25.500
The genres that we still have today
are formulated at this period.

00:13:25.500 --> 00:13:28.540
Detective films, societies,
melodramas, horror.

00:13:28.540 --> 00:13:29.840
They're all there.

00:13:29.840 --> 00:13:32.000
So even science fiction is there.

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:34.240
The formats, as I've mentioned,
the multiple-reel film,

00:13:34.240 --> 00:13:37.760
the idea that a reel movie is at
least an hour and 10 minutes long.

00:13:37.760 --> 00:13:42.340
And the dramaturgy, the
structuring of stories.

00:13:42.340 --> 00:13:45.830
The thing is when you have a
longer film like a feature,

00:13:45.830 --> 00:13:47.280
how do you complicate it?

00:13:47.280 --> 00:13:50.410
How do you tell a story
that lasts 50 or 60 minutes?

00:13:50.410 --> 00:13:53.950
Kind of between a novel and a short
story, how do you fill that out

00:13:53.950 --> 00:13:56.680
with an interesting plot that
will keep people interested?

00:13:56.680 --> 00:13:59.600
Well, my argument is this.

00:13:59.600 --> 00:14:04.600
Because of this immense growth
in audiences and film culture,

00:14:04.600 --> 00:14:08.980
and the development of the long
film, there's a pressure to develop

00:14:08.980 --> 00:14:14.930
to use the medium in ways, to use
film, staging, shooting, cutting,

00:14:14.930 --> 00:14:17.680 position:56%
performance, in ways that are suited

00:14:17.680 --> 00:14:20.750
to telling these more
lengthy and complex stories.

00:14:20.750 --> 00:14:24.220
So, a couple of trends develop.

00:14:24.220 --> 00:14:27.180
I'm being schematic here for
the purposes of exposition,

00:14:27.180 --> 00:14:29.740
but I think this is
pretty much true.

00:14:29.740 --> 00:14:33.470
On the one hand, filmmakers decide
the thing we've seen already.

00:14:33.470 --> 00:14:37.130
The option that we mentioned, we
cut the scene up as John Ford does

00:14:37.130 --> 00:14:38.770
for instance, in straight shooting.

00:14:38.770 --> 00:14:40.070
You're going to have a western.

00:14:40.070 --> 00:14:41.500
You're going to have a
showdown with western.

00:14:41.500 --> 00:14:45.230 position:56%
Big close ups of the two guys facing
each other down on the city street,

00:14:45.230 --> 00:14:48.090
just like [inaudible] would, just
the way what Clint Eastwood would,

00:14:48.090 --> 00:14:50.100
the same, the editing option.

00:14:50.100 --> 00:14:53.330
The other option is to do
things a little differently.

00:14:53.330 --> 00:14:55.730
You do it through staging.

00:14:55.730 --> 00:14:58.900
Instead of cutting the scene
up, you move your actors

00:14:58.900 --> 00:15:02.470
around the frame in
various patterns.

00:15:02.470 --> 00:15:04.770
That's the loser.

00:15:05.990 --> 00:15:11.850
There are many options, or many
tasks that you need to fulfill

00:15:11.850 --> 00:15:14.030
if you're going to use
film to tell stories.

00:15:14.030 --> 00:15:16.730
You have to engage the
audience emotionally.

00:15:16.730 --> 00:15:19.200
You have to find ways to align
them with characters and so on.

00:15:19.200 --> 00:15:20.500
There are many different things.

00:15:20.500 --> 00:15:21.800
I'm just going to focus on one,

00:15:21.800 --> 00:15:23.950
which is kind of a
precondition for all the others.

00:15:23.950 --> 00:15:29.800 position:56%
And that is directing the audience's
attention to follow a story on stage

00:15:29.800 --> 00:15:33.210
in a novel, wherever, in a ballet,

00:15:33.210 --> 00:15:35.650
whatever narrative form
you're talking about.

00:15:35.650 --> 00:15:37.970
The attention of the
audience has to be focused

00:15:37.970 --> 00:15:41.240
on particular items
of, in the array.

00:15:41.240 --> 00:15:44.470
So the question is given film,
how do you focus attention?

00:15:44.470 --> 00:15:46.700
Well, editing offers the choice.

00:15:46.700 --> 00:15:48.000
Editing says, here's how you do it.

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:49.610
You cut the scenes up.

00:15:49.610 --> 00:15:53.120
You either cut them by
showing two events or more,

00:15:53.120 --> 00:15:56.690
taking place at roughly the same
time, and you switch from one

00:15:56.690 --> 00:15:58.510
to the other, so-called
crosscutting.

00:15:58.510 --> 00:16:03.010
As The Birth of a Nation is in
Birth of a Nation with Griffith,

00:16:03.010 --> 00:16:06.150
while Lillian Gish is
besieged in this parlor,

00:16:06.150 --> 00:16:08.260
the Ku Klux Clan is
riding to her rescue,

00:16:08.260 --> 00:16:09.560
back and forth, back and forth.

00:16:09.560 --> 00:16:11.740
And then so, the eyes
are like pointed up,

00:16:11.740 --> 00:16:13.210
novels did this all the time.

00:16:13.210 --> 00:16:15.680
This is not-- This is
simply a straightforward,

00:16:15.680 --> 00:16:20.030
but kind of intensifying and
focusing of what novels have done

00:16:20.030 --> 00:16:21.910
in terms of intercut chapters

00:16:21.910 --> 00:16:23.980
or even intercut sections
within a chapter.

00:16:23.980 --> 00:16:27.820
While X is strolling in the
park, Y is murdering his wife,

00:16:27.820 --> 00:16:29.540
back and forth, back and forth.

00:16:29.540 --> 00:16:30.860
So that's adapted to film

00:16:30.860 --> 00:16:33.170
and editing is necessary
to make it work.

00:16:33.170 --> 00:16:36.930
The other option is so-called
scene analysis or scene dissection

00:16:36.930 --> 00:16:41.090
where you'd take a master
shot or this and break it

00:16:41.090 --> 00:16:43.140
up into its component parts.

00:16:43.140 --> 00:16:46.090
So while the little colonel is
recovering from this battle wounds

00:16:46.090 --> 00:16:49.770
in the bivouac hospital, he's lying
there and we got a shot of him.

00:16:49.770 --> 00:16:52.420
And he hears Lillian Gish
playing her mandolin,

00:16:52.420 --> 00:16:54.250
I guess that is her banjo.

00:16:54.250 --> 00:16:58.140
While we understand the emotional
interaction that's starting

00:16:58.140 --> 00:17:00.070
to emerge between them.

00:17:00.070 --> 00:17:01.790
And it's the focusing
of the attention

00:17:01.790 --> 00:17:05.700
with the separate close-up shots of
them that drives our understanding

00:17:05.700 --> 00:17:07.840
and response to the drama.

00:17:07.840 --> 00:17:10.840
So editing does that focus
of attention for you.

00:17:10.840 --> 00:17:14.150
And that's what happens essentially
in the course of the themes.

00:17:14.150 --> 00:17:16.280
The dominant style
for handling those one

00:17:16.280 --> 00:17:20.610
on one encounters is a standardized
pattern of continuity editing.

00:17:20.610 --> 00:17:21.910
This and other things,

00:17:21.910 --> 00:17:23.450
I'll be mentioning some
that you've seen before.

00:17:23.450 --> 00:17:26.780
At a 1917 film based on
Wilkie Collins' novel,

00:17:26.780 --> 00:17:29.980
"The Woman in White",
you'd get a master shot,

00:17:29.980 --> 00:17:31.690
and then you'd get a closer view

00:17:31.690 --> 00:17:35.100
as Count Fosco opens the
door and Marian is there.

00:17:35.100 --> 00:17:37.580
And then you'd get a
reverse angle on the husband

00:17:37.580 --> 00:17:40.640
who has been standing off the one
side, looking suspiciously at her.

00:17:40.640 --> 00:17:44.010
And then another view of the
three, but a different framing.

00:17:44.010 --> 00:17:47.640
And by this point, they're thinking
OK, we don't need to see that,

00:17:47.640 --> 00:17:51.280
all of that painting and all
that candle around the left.

00:17:51.280 --> 00:17:53.160
We just go tighter
in on the characters.

00:17:53.160 --> 00:17:56.430
This is very modern and it's
very much what has developed

00:17:56.430 --> 00:17:58.390
on those period based on editing.

00:17:58.390 --> 00:18:00.790
So for moment to moment,
your attention is focused

00:18:00.790 --> 00:18:03.530
on what each character
is doing or saying to,

00:18:03.530 --> 00:18:05.680
in relation to the others.

00:18:05.680 --> 00:18:08.490
And what develops at
this point among critics

00:18:08.490 --> 00:18:12.370
and historians is a kind of
chauvinistic claim about editing.

00:18:12.370 --> 00:18:14.150
It's so powerful.

00:18:14.150 --> 00:18:18.090 position:56%
It transcends time and space because
it cuts around all over the place.

00:18:18.090 --> 00:18:22.580
It focuses our attention, rivets
us to particular things going on.

00:18:22.580 --> 00:18:23.880
It has to be.

00:18:23.880 --> 00:18:25.370
It's not only a great tool.

00:18:25.370 --> 00:18:29.420
It has to be the uniquely
cinematic technique.

00:18:29.420 --> 00:18:32.900
No other medium has an exact
equivalent for editing.

00:18:32.900 --> 00:18:35.390
So the theorists and critics say.

00:18:35.390 --> 00:18:41.070
And in a way, cinema was destined
to reveal its essence as editing.

00:18:41.070 --> 00:18:43.940
More and more, if you read, people
in the 20s and 30s are saying,

00:18:43.940 --> 00:18:45.510
we had to get rid of all
that other stuff in order

00:18:45.510 --> 00:18:47.880
to find the real true
essence of cinema.

00:18:47.880 --> 00:18:50.850
Its fate was to be an
editing-based medium.

00:18:50.850 --> 00:18:53.620
Why? Well, it directs and
maintains attention as we've seen.

00:18:53.620 --> 00:18:57.080
And it permits what we
might call camera ubiquity.

00:18:57.080 --> 00:19:00.510
That camera can be
anywhere in time and space.

00:19:00.510 --> 00:19:05.660
And then, the cut becomes a kind
of beat or kick, a little bump.

00:19:05.660 --> 00:19:06.960
You may perceive it.

00:19:06.960 --> 00:19:08.260
You may not perceive it.

00:19:08.260 --> 00:19:10.190
Ideally, you don't
perceive it most of the time

00:19:10.190 --> 00:19:13.120
because the filmmaker's technique
is aiming to make it invisible.

00:19:13.120 --> 00:19:15.950
But sometimes, as in this
later segment I'd show you

00:19:15.950 --> 00:19:19.520
from Hidden Figures, actually
it functions as a beat.

00:19:19.520 --> 00:19:22.340
As the couple kiss, we cut
to an extreme long shot

00:19:22.340 --> 00:19:23.670
that we had not seen before.

00:19:23.670 --> 00:19:25.510
But it gives a kind of
code into the scene.

00:19:25.510 --> 00:19:27.020
It concludes the scene.

00:19:27.020 --> 00:19:29.640
OK, we're backing discreetly
away from them.

00:19:29.640 --> 00:19:30.940
This is so powerful.

00:19:30.940 --> 00:19:32.240
How can you not fake?

00:19:32.240 --> 00:19:34.930
This is the engine
that drives cinema.

00:19:34.930 --> 00:19:36.980
You'd get so many--
It buys you so much.

00:19:36.980 --> 00:19:38.540
It gets you so many advantages.

00:19:38.540 --> 00:19:40.560
Take this which I found
here in the archive.

00:19:40.560 --> 00:19:41.860
But I never heard of it before,

00:19:41.860 --> 00:19:44.510
it's a very interesting film
called, "The Running Fight".

00:19:44.510 --> 00:19:49.850 position:56%
Earlier in the scene, the curtain is
revealed to have someone behind it.

00:19:49.850 --> 00:19:51.340
There, you can see the
couple in foreground,

00:19:51.340 --> 00:19:52.690
the father and the daughter.

00:19:52.690 --> 00:19:54.820
And someone is peering in at them.

00:19:54.820 --> 00:19:57.910
Later, a different setup,
camera setup of that sort

00:19:57.910 --> 00:20:01.940
of office laboratory, shows the
men gather around the retorts

00:20:01.940 --> 00:20:04.100
and stuff and the curtain.

00:20:04.100 --> 00:20:09.210
And then thanks to good old camera
ubiquity, boom, we're in closer

00:20:09.210 --> 00:20:12.180
to the hand that emerges
from the curtain.

00:20:12.180 --> 00:20:15.510
Then back to the master
shot, the shot is fired,

00:20:15.510 --> 00:20:17.840
back to the hand, the
pistol is dropped.

00:20:17.840 --> 00:20:20.130
So, you could not miss it.

00:20:20.130 --> 00:20:24.470
You could not misunderstand
that that pistol shot was fired

00:20:24.470 --> 00:20:25.890
from behind that curtain.

00:20:25.890 --> 00:20:28.850
If we'd had only the long
shot, this little shot here,

00:20:28.850 --> 00:20:31.200
who knows what you
would have thought.

00:20:31.200 --> 00:20:34.250
Interestingly later in the film,
we do find out who fires the shot.

00:20:34.250 --> 00:20:36.580
It's a woman who's been taken
to a mental institution.

00:20:36.580 --> 00:20:39.740
She's had a kind of
breakdown after doing this.

00:20:39.740 --> 00:20:43.230
And so we see her on
her deathbed confessing.

00:20:43.230 --> 00:20:46.760
And what's done is on the
left-hand side of the frame,

00:20:46.760 --> 00:20:48.440
she's lying on her bed
and there's an attendant,

00:20:48.440 --> 00:20:50.960
you can see I hope,
bending over her.

00:20:50.960 --> 00:20:56.140
The right-hand side of the frame
is a replay of the shooting

00:20:56.140 --> 00:20:58.530
from behind the curtain,
if you can see

00:20:58.530 --> 00:21:02.510
that silhouette there
on the front-right.

00:21:02.510 --> 00:21:04.870
Here. This is her, shooting.

00:21:04.870 --> 00:21:10.150
Here's the scene-- the present-time
scene of her in the institution.

00:21:10.150 --> 00:21:13.610
So the camera has not
only jumped back in time,

00:21:13.610 --> 00:21:18.650
it's given us two spaces and
two times in the same framing.

00:21:18.650 --> 00:21:21.710
You know, this is a celebration
of the power of cinema.

00:21:21.710 --> 00:21:23.790
And of course it's not-- you
imagine, well, we could do this

00:21:23.790 --> 00:21:25.770
in a comic strip, sure,
but it doesn't move.

00:21:25.770 --> 00:21:30.800
One of the things I discovered or
at least I should have known before

00:21:30.800 --> 00:21:32.100
but kind of was brought home

00:21:32.100 --> 00:21:34.720
to me during my stay here was
what I might call the punch

00:21:34.720 --> 00:21:36.020
of the axial cut.

00:21:36.020 --> 00:21:37.460
Now an axial cut is editing

00:21:37.460 --> 00:21:41.240
which doesn't vary the
angle on the subject.

00:21:41.240 --> 00:21:43.990
It comes right in on
the camera axis.

00:21:43.990 --> 00:21:46.860 position:56%
So the camera is pointed this way,
we have a shot from here, then here,

00:21:46.860 --> 00:21:49.670
then here, boom, boom,
boom, straight in.

00:21:49.670 --> 00:21:53.600
So for instance, in "The Typhoon",
while woman's Asian lover,

00:21:53.600 --> 00:21:58.620
Japanese lover is arguing with
her French lover in his study,

00:21:58.620 --> 00:22:01.380 position:56%
we see her listening in the bedroom.

00:22:01.380 --> 00:22:04.580
And we cut back to the quarrel
between the men and we cut back

00:22:04.580 --> 00:22:07.040
to her, but note that we've
had axial cut back to her.

00:22:07.040 --> 00:22:08.430
It's punching up our attention.

00:22:08.430 --> 00:22:09.980
It's focusing our attention.

00:22:09.980 --> 00:22:13.640
Just in case, you know,
remember, she's listening.

00:22:13.640 --> 00:22:17.320
Also, it's a kind of mimicry
of her act of attending.

00:22:17.320 --> 00:22:18.800
The fact that she's focusing more

00:22:18.800 --> 00:22:21.460
and more what the men
are saying makes us--

00:22:21.460 --> 00:22:24.440
is echoed in a way by
this closer view of her.

00:22:24.440 --> 00:22:28.700
And finally, as the quarrel gets
going, we go even tighter to her,

00:22:28.700 --> 00:22:31.960
boom, boom, boom, three axial
cuts on her sort of sandwiched

00:22:31.960 --> 00:22:33.970
between shots of the men.

00:22:33.970 --> 00:22:36.590
For even bigger punch, I
found in "The Juggernaut",

00:22:36.590 --> 00:22:39.040
a magnificent film,
unfortunately only a fragment,

00:22:39.040 --> 00:22:41.490
released the same week as
"Birth of a Nation" actually.

00:22:41.490 --> 00:22:44.770
A woman has been rescued from a
train wreck that's taken place

00:22:44.770 --> 00:22:48.530 position:56%
on a bridge, the bridge is
collapsing, the cars are underwater.

00:22:48.530 --> 00:22:49.970
It's a fantastic scene.

00:22:49.970 --> 00:22:53.800
And she's been rescued, she's
hauled up by the man who loves her,

00:22:53.800 --> 00:22:56.850
but it looks like she's dead.

00:22:56.850 --> 00:22:59.200
The axial cut takes us in closer.

00:22:59.200 --> 00:23:00.540
Is she dead or isn't she?

00:23:00.540 --> 00:23:03.080
Bang, it's a very percussive
kind of cut.

00:23:03.080 --> 00:23:04.980
And then again, in on her.

00:23:04.980 --> 00:23:08.660
So here, there's nothing in
between, we go boom, boom, boom.

00:23:08.660 --> 00:23:12.070
And then back a bit, and
there's the suspense moment,

00:23:12.070 --> 00:23:13.520
will she revive or not?

00:23:13.520 --> 00:23:15.350
Is she really dead?

00:23:15.350 --> 00:23:17.440
Cut to the close-up of
her lifting her head

00:23:17.440 --> 00:23:19.860
and cut back to the master shot.

00:23:19.860 --> 00:23:21.790
He doesn't even realize
it but we do.

00:23:21.790 --> 00:23:23.440
That's in alignment with us.

00:23:23.440 --> 00:23:26.420
So here, all the cuts are
along that camera axis

00:23:26.420 --> 00:23:30.700
and are being used very carefully
to enhance the emotional effect

00:23:30.700 --> 00:23:33.770
of what we're seeing, the
suspense of the moment and kind

00:23:33.770 --> 00:23:38.280 position:56%
of riveting our attention to whether
her eyelids will flutter or not.

00:23:38.280 --> 00:23:39.580
One more example.

00:23:39.580 --> 00:23:41.200
This hasn't gone away.

00:23:41.200 --> 00:23:42.860
The axial cut is still with us.

00:23:42.860 --> 00:23:45.240 position:56%
You see it on TV almost every night.

00:23:45.240 --> 00:23:47.960
I picked a film I like,
"The Hunt for Red October",

00:23:47.960 --> 00:23:52.330
when our two heroes are being fired
upon from the guy in the stadium

00:23:52.330 --> 00:23:55.350
up above, the station
up above, boom, boom,

00:23:55.350 --> 00:23:58.480
boom, axial cuts all the way.

00:23:58.480 --> 00:24:01.380
And most action films use
axial cuts for this kind of,

00:24:01.380 --> 00:24:03.040
you know, fist-in-your-face look.

00:24:03.040 --> 00:24:05.590
So that's an example.

00:24:05.590 --> 00:24:09.690
Camera ubiquity from narrative
purposes gives you something else,

00:24:09.690 --> 00:24:13.910
it buys you omniscience, can also
have that bump or pump effect

00:24:13.910 --> 00:24:16.970
that I mentioned but it
lets you go anywhere.

00:24:16.970 --> 00:24:18.950
Here's a beautiful example
from another film I saw

00:24:18.950 --> 00:24:20.600
of Rich Motion Picture
Division [phonetic],

00:24:20.600 --> 00:24:22.590
"The Bargain", also
by Reginald Barker.

00:24:22.590 --> 00:24:28.130
William S. Hart is set on sides
by the sheriff and his men.

00:24:28.130 --> 00:24:31.350
He's trapped in his room and we get
a master shot of him in the room.

00:24:31.350 --> 00:24:34.610
We go outside to the door
he's pointing his pistol at.

00:24:34.610 --> 00:24:39.340 position:56%
The sheriff and his men are outside,
but they're on the other side too,

00:24:39.340 --> 00:24:42.060
a closer shot of Bill
looking at the door.

00:24:42.060 --> 00:24:44.200 position:56%
And now we go walk to the other side

00:24:44.200 --> 00:24:47.110
where we see the deputy
hammering away at the window.

00:24:47.110 --> 00:24:50.140
He starts to break the window
in fact to kind of get--

00:24:50.140 --> 00:24:52.610
to surround or ambush Bill.

00:24:52.610 --> 00:24:55.270
And then we got the shot completely
from around the other side.

00:24:55.270 --> 00:24:56.570
So we can see the deputy

00:24:56.570 --> 00:25:00.140
and actually see the glass
breaking in this shot.

00:25:00.140 --> 00:25:02.150
So the camera has been able
to hop around anywhere.

00:25:02.150 --> 00:25:04.260
It can go inside the
room, outside the room,

00:25:04.260 --> 00:25:06.490 position:56%
at different points within the room.

00:25:06.490 --> 00:25:10.010
Thanks to editing, completely
clear, completely coherent

00:25:10.010 --> 00:25:12.080
and focusing your attention
instant by instant

00:25:12.080 --> 00:25:14.200
on each dramatic development.

00:25:14.200 --> 00:25:17.000
Now he really is surrounded.

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:21.430 position:56%
So as I said, by 1917, editing wins.

00:25:21.430 --> 00:25:26.330
You are not a competent filmmaker
if you don't use editing by 1917

00:25:26.330 --> 00:25:28.590
in America, in America this is.

00:25:28.590 --> 00:25:29.890
There are a few refinements.

00:25:29.890 --> 00:25:31.720
I'll just mention one enhancement.

00:25:31.720 --> 00:25:36.850
"Victory", we see it a little
bit later, 1919, filmmakers start

00:25:36.850 --> 00:25:39.090
to give a kind of redundant
cue to let us--

00:25:39.090 --> 00:25:40.660
to remind us that these
characters were

00:25:40.660 --> 00:25:43.780
in proximity, so shoulders come in.

00:25:43.780 --> 00:25:48.290
You start to have what we call
now OTSs, over-the-shoulder shots.

00:25:48.290 --> 00:25:50.780
This come in the same golden
period I'm talking about.

00:25:50.780 --> 00:25:53.170
If you love shoulders,
you'll love Hollywood cinema

00:25:53.170 --> 00:25:55.050
because they are everywhere.

00:25:55.050 --> 00:25:56.780
And again, same thing we find

00:25:56.780 --> 00:25:59.600
in hidden figures,
shoulders all the time.

00:25:59.600 --> 00:26:00.900
So that's one of the enhancements.

00:26:00.900 --> 00:26:02.200
There are a few others.

00:26:02.200 --> 00:26:04.590
But basically, the
foundation has been laid.

00:26:04.590 --> 00:26:07.160
Editing is the dominant
mode of expression

00:26:07.160 --> 00:26:10.450
for commercial mass market cinema.

00:26:10.450 --> 00:26:11.750
So what's the alternative?

00:26:11.750 --> 00:26:13.800
What did editing defeat?

00:26:13.800 --> 00:26:17.530
Well, what's been come to be called
mostly by film scholars rather

00:26:17.530 --> 00:26:20.870
than filmmakers, tableau cinema.

00:26:20.870 --> 00:26:24.350
Here, the emphasis is on
staging rather than cutting

00:26:24.350 --> 00:26:29.080
and a fixed camera rather than
that camera ubiquity that we get

00:26:29.080 --> 00:26:31.940
with the power of editing.

00:26:31.940 --> 00:26:35.570
It's very strong in European
cinema in the period I'm discussing

00:26:35.570 --> 00:26:37.940
where editing is generally
more minimal.

00:26:37.940 --> 00:26:41.200
Take this early example,
beautiful example, very early,

00:26:41.200 --> 00:26:43.750 position:56%
"The Assassination of Duc du Guise".

00:26:43.750 --> 00:26:46.300
This is-- You might think
it's like a theater play.

00:26:46.300 --> 00:26:47.700
It looks like very theatrical.

00:26:47.700 --> 00:26:50.360
I want to try to convince
you it's not theatrical.

00:26:50.360 --> 00:26:53.820
But at any rate, this becomes
very elaborate in Europe,

00:26:53.820 --> 00:26:58.440
very refined in a film like "Life
of an Evangelist", the Danish film.

00:26:58.440 --> 00:27:02.510
You get shots of incredible
complexity in a single framing,

00:27:02.510 --> 00:27:04.400
with apertures of people
poking in and out,

00:27:04.400 --> 00:27:05.750
the sort of peekaboo effect.

00:27:05.750 --> 00:27:07.500
It's all over the place.

00:27:07.500 --> 00:27:11.400 position:56%
It really is a very refined and
delicate art and it hangs on longer,

00:27:11.400 --> 00:27:14.990
this tableau approach,
in Europe than in the US.

00:27:14.990 --> 00:27:16.290
But what is it really?

00:27:16.290 --> 00:27:17.590
I'll try to explain.

00:27:17.590 --> 00:27:19.810
At first glance, as I mentioned,

00:27:19.810 --> 00:27:22.360
it seems very theatrical,
and that's not wrong.

00:27:22.360 --> 00:27:24.870
If you think in terms of
acting or performance,

00:27:24.870 --> 00:27:28.610
it does draw on theatrical
traditions,

00:27:28.610 --> 00:27:31.370
such as the Italian diva
films where you have kind

00:27:31.370 --> 00:27:34.560
of operatic acting style
captured by the camera.

00:27:34.560 --> 00:27:36.630
It wouldn't be wrong
to call that dimension

00:27:36.630 --> 00:27:39.220
of expression there
theatrical I think.

00:27:39.220 --> 00:27:41.950
But in another respect, it's
very indebted to painting

00:27:41.950 --> 00:27:44.040
and in fact is somewhat
anti-theatrical.

00:27:44.040 --> 00:27:47.150
If you think about pictorialist
filmmakers like the Yevgeni Bauer

00:27:47.150 --> 00:27:51.030
in Russia, we have images
that you just want to look at

00:27:51.030 --> 00:27:52.660
and look at for a long time.

00:27:52.660 --> 00:27:54.150
Allan Levinson [assumed
spelling] talked about this.

00:27:54.150 --> 00:27:57.750
You want to soak yourself in them
and they seem to owe much more

00:27:57.750 --> 00:28:00.780
to the traditions of
academic 19th century painting

00:28:00.780 --> 00:28:03.670
than they do to theater.

00:28:03.670 --> 00:28:07.640
But I'm going to try to argue
that film is partly theatrical,

00:28:07.640 --> 00:28:11.850 position:56%
partly painterly, but also
something else, something different.

00:28:11.850 --> 00:28:14.550
And I have to give an example
from an early Danish film,

00:28:14.550 --> 00:28:17.570
one of my favorites
called "Pat Corner".

00:28:17.570 --> 00:28:20.590
There are scenes in "Pat
Corner"-- It's a detective film.

00:28:20.590 --> 00:28:23.500
There are scenes in "Pat Corner"
that are indeed very theatrical.

00:28:23.500 --> 00:28:28.140
The one I show you is of a man
trying to break into a bank

00:28:28.140 --> 00:28:30.330
that has all these
different bank vaults in it.

00:28:30.330 --> 00:28:33.380
And he doesn't seem to notice
that he could simply walk

00:28:33.380 --> 00:28:35.630
around the edge of the wall.

00:28:35.630 --> 00:28:39.200 position:56%
The theatrical convention is that
he is on the other side of the wall,

00:28:39.200 --> 00:28:40.880
burrowing in while
the guard is listening

00:28:40.880 --> 00:28:43.470
for what's the noise
being caused here.

00:28:43.470 --> 00:28:44.770
We just take for granted

00:28:44.770 --> 00:28:46.070
that there's been a
fourth wall sliced away

00:28:46.070 --> 00:28:48.170
and he really can't walk around.

00:28:48.170 --> 00:28:50.860
That's a classic theatrical
convention.

00:28:50.860 --> 00:28:54.620
But, later, at the end of the
film, when the client comes

00:28:54.620 --> 00:28:57.410
in to congratulate our detective
Pat Corner for a great solution

00:28:57.410 --> 00:29:00.400
to the case, he comes
striding into his office.

00:29:00.400 --> 00:29:02.750
And you can see him
there, moving in I hope.

00:29:02.750 --> 00:29:06.230
And then he takes up a position
to thank Pat and shake his hand.

00:29:06.230 --> 00:29:10.390 position:56%
In the course of that though, he
blocks that third man who's a clerk.

00:29:10.390 --> 00:29:13.060
You see the clerk there in that
second shot standing there?

00:29:13.060 --> 00:29:19.070
The client, the third frame I'm
showing you, stands in his way.

00:29:19.070 --> 00:29:20.660
You can't see him.

00:29:20.660 --> 00:29:25.470
The clerk knows this and so,
he takes a step to one side.

00:29:25.470 --> 00:29:28.860
He just steps in to let-- just
moves like this so you can see him,

00:29:28.860 --> 00:29:32.540
just like me and this stupid
column, you know, like this, this.

00:29:32.540 --> 00:29:38.040
Well, Pat steps in front of
him and says, "Oh, no problem,

00:29:38.040 --> 00:29:40.540
I was happy to solve your case."

00:29:40.540 --> 00:29:42.860 position:56%
But the clerk is not to be defeated,

00:29:42.860 --> 00:29:44.970
because he just takes
another step back to the left

00:29:44.970 --> 00:29:48.610
and we can see him
again, scene-stealer, OK?

00:29:48.610 --> 00:29:52.550
My point is it wouldn't
work on the stage.

00:29:52.550 --> 00:29:54.010
It could not work on the stage.

00:29:54.010 --> 00:29:55.310
It isn't theatrical.

00:29:55.310 --> 00:29:57.610
It's purely cinematic.

00:29:57.610 --> 00:30:01.010
Why? Well, because at
least in Western Theater,

00:30:01.010 --> 00:30:05.380
but a lot of Asian Theaters
too, at least those I know of,

00:30:05.380 --> 00:30:09.560
the audience can be arranged
in a circle or semicircle.

00:30:09.560 --> 00:30:16.030
But the stage is lateral, the stage
is a rectangle, it's horizontal,

00:30:16.030 --> 00:30:18.850
as here in this room, this
is a theatrical setup.

00:30:18.850 --> 00:30:22.240
My playing space is this stretch
right here, and you're arranged

00:30:22.240 --> 00:30:24.210
in a kind of semicircle around it.

00:30:24.210 --> 00:30:26.410
Well, if we go back to Elizabethan
theater, back still further

00:30:26.410 --> 00:30:29.430
to ancient Greece,
we find this array.

00:30:29.430 --> 00:30:32.420
And it still continues into the
Renaissance with Lope de Vega,

00:30:32.420 --> 00:30:36.680 position:56%
it continues with Eugene O'Neill and
other playwrights using these kinds

00:30:36.680 --> 00:30:41.450
of horizontal, lateral
staging as the norm in theatre.

00:30:41.450 --> 00:30:42.860
And it makes sense
for the very reason

00:30:42.860 --> 00:30:47.240
that you could see right
now, sight lines, right?

00:30:47.240 --> 00:30:50.980
Every one of you has a different
sight line to me right now.

00:30:50.980 --> 00:30:53.140
No two angles are the same.

00:30:53.140 --> 00:30:57.430
So, if we're going to have me
and maybe my co-players hashed

00:30:57.430 --> 00:30:59.040
out across here, interacting,

00:30:59.040 --> 00:31:01.460
we have to do it pretty
much on a horizontal line.

00:31:01.460 --> 00:31:03.580
It can have some variance.

00:31:03.580 --> 00:31:06.310
I can turn my back if you
want to look at-- if I want--

00:31:06.310 --> 00:31:09.670 position:56%
the director wants you to look at a
player, I can go on stage of course.

00:31:09.670 --> 00:31:16.760
But basically, this is the axis of
action in theatre, but not in film,

00:31:16.760 --> 00:31:18.650
because film isn't theatre.

00:31:18.650 --> 00:31:19.950
Film is a projection system.

00:31:19.950 --> 00:31:22.180
It's an optical projection system.

00:31:22.180 --> 00:31:24.330
In that respect, it's like
Renaissance perspective,

00:31:24.330 --> 00:31:26.240
classic Renaissance perspective.

00:31:26.240 --> 00:31:27.950
I'll show you this
example from the period.

00:31:27.950 --> 00:31:30.790
People at that time were
thinking about this.

00:31:30.790 --> 00:31:33.590
It's a pyramid, a tipped-over
pyramid

00:31:33.590 --> 00:31:35.690
with the point resting on the lens.

00:31:35.690 --> 00:31:39.170
That's the playing space
of every film shot.

00:31:39.170 --> 00:31:43.800 position:56%
Indeed, certainly, every live action
film shot, it's even that way in CGI

00:31:43.800 --> 00:31:47.270
and in animation as
well, for the most part.

00:31:47.270 --> 00:31:49.210
There are some more experimental.

00:31:49.210 --> 00:31:53.020
But the most part, this is
the optical rule of cinema.

00:31:53.020 --> 00:31:55.450
Even though when you look at a
film frame, it seems to be a space,

00:31:55.450 --> 00:31:57.240
a cubic space with something
just sliced out of it,

00:31:57.240 --> 00:32:00.950
and all those people standing in
the box, mm-mm, it's that shape.

00:32:00.950 --> 00:32:02.490
That's what-- That's the contents

00:32:02.490 --> 00:32:05.770
of the container, that
tapering pyramid.

00:32:05.770 --> 00:32:09.550
And indeed, in 1913, very
helpful for my purposes,

00:32:09.550 --> 00:32:12.350
a screenwriting manual
spelled it all out.

00:32:12.350 --> 00:32:18.270
This is the stage base, right
there, that pie-slice-shaped wedge

00:32:18.270 --> 00:32:23.170
of action is what the camera
captures, different from theatre.

00:32:23.170 --> 00:32:24.470
OK, so what?

00:32:24.470 --> 00:32:27.770
Well, here's an example
by the way of a film

00:32:27.770 --> 00:32:29.620 position:56%
that includes a theatre performance.

00:32:29.620 --> 00:32:31.870
And you can see the difference
I think rather clearly.

00:32:31.870 --> 00:32:36.460 position:56%
In the stage in the distance, people
are spread out like a gatefold.

00:32:36.460 --> 00:32:39.220
But in the space in front
of it, people arrayed

00:32:39.220 --> 00:32:43.940
in all these different angles,
but our camera sees only one spot.

00:32:43.940 --> 00:32:49.040
The camera has only one sightline,
wherever the camera happens to be.

00:32:49.040 --> 00:32:52.650
By the way, that film was
by Sergio Leone's father.

00:32:52.650 --> 00:32:56.020
So what happens now with
the task of storytelling?

00:32:56.020 --> 00:32:59.140
What happens with the
problem of guiding attention?

00:32:59.140 --> 00:33:02.840
How do you do that with
that kind of playing space?

00:33:02.840 --> 00:33:05.620
Well, my argument would be that
the punch and bumps that you feel

00:33:05.620 --> 00:33:09.780
with editing, it gets replaced
by something we might call flow,

00:33:09.780 --> 00:33:14.400
a continuous mobile changing
of what we're seeing onscreen.

00:33:14.400 --> 00:33:17.170
A simply example from a
fairly kind of crude example

00:33:17.170 --> 00:33:19.350
but it's illustrative
from the Tannhäuser film

00:33:19.350 --> 00:33:21.000
"David Copperfield",
not in your collection.

00:33:21.000 --> 00:33:24.110
I took this from a DVD.

00:33:24.110 --> 00:33:25.660
Two features I think
are worth mentioning.

00:33:25.660 --> 00:33:30.290
First, because of that tapering,
that triangular wedge-shaped piece

00:33:30.290 --> 00:33:34.370
of space, there's a lot of
depth in a cinematic image.

00:33:34.370 --> 00:33:37.850
Theatre space is shallow,
film space can be deep.

00:33:37.850 --> 00:33:39.630
So, you have depth staging.

00:33:39.630 --> 00:33:43.000
Here in "David Copperfield",
when Betsey comes to the office

00:33:43.000 --> 00:33:46.450
and greeted by Uriah Heep and
Micawber sitting there at the desk,

00:33:46.450 --> 00:33:50.880
everybody gets their own little
piece of the space, foreground,

00:33:50.880 --> 00:33:54.250
middle ground and background.

00:33:54.250 --> 00:33:58.720
That means you can do something
that's not so effective on theatre,

00:33:58.720 --> 00:34:00.560
what I call blocking and revealing.

00:34:00.560 --> 00:34:03.350
You can have the figures
in the foreground mask

00:34:03.350 --> 00:34:06.330
at certain times what's
in the background.

00:34:06.330 --> 00:34:11.460
So what happens is as the man
who's ruined Betsey's investments,

00:34:11.460 --> 00:34:16.110
I forget his name, you
probably remember, apologizes.

00:34:16.110 --> 00:34:20.070
Becky steps over so you can't
really see Uriah Heep's reaction.

00:34:20.070 --> 00:34:21.500
He's engineered the whole thing.

00:34:21.500 --> 00:34:22.800
He's stolen the money.

00:34:22.800 --> 00:34:26.560
And while David talks with
Micawber there on the back,

00:34:26.560 --> 00:34:28.480
the contrite lawyer bends down.

00:34:28.480 --> 00:34:32.920
Betsey listens to him and then
bends down to forgive him.

00:34:32.920 --> 00:34:35.020
And then you get Uriah
Heep's reaction.

00:34:35.020 --> 00:34:38.820
See in there on the far right,
peeking and gloating there.

00:34:38.820 --> 00:34:41.400
Now, as I said, this is a TV
frame, so there would be more

00:34:41.400 --> 00:34:44.740
for the original audience to see,
and it's a simple example of this.

00:34:44.740 --> 00:34:48.800
But you see how the revelation
of his reaction has been delayed

00:34:48.800 --> 00:34:51.010
by the blocking of his face.

00:34:51.010 --> 00:34:53.810
And when Betsey moves,
he can pop out.

00:34:53.810 --> 00:34:56.440 position:56%
This seems really simple, but it
couldn't work that way on the stage.

00:34:56.440 --> 00:34:59.060
Some of the peoples in the-- people
in the audience would see him,

00:34:59.060 --> 00:35:03.070
Uriah, all the way through if
they were sitting over there.

00:35:03.070 --> 00:35:08.200
So that's kind of flow yielded by
depth, gets picked up undeveloped

00:35:08.200 --> 00:35:10.720
through this blocking
and-- revealing strategy.

00:35:10.720 --> 00:35:13.020
It's worth mentioning that the
kind of depth the people think

00:35:13.020 --> 00:35:17.270
about in cinema usually is
associated with the 1940s.

00:35:17.270 --> 00:35:20.360
We tend to think of Orson
Welles and his comrades

00:35:20.360 --> 00:35:24.600
as developing deep space
or deep focus cinema.

00:35:24.600 --> 00:35:27.140
And it's true, he does in the '40s.

00:35:27.140 --> 00:35:30.190
But I would point out
that the foreground planes

00:35:30.190 --> 00:35:32.700
in the '40s cinema
tend to be much closer,

00:35:32.700 --> 00:35:34.920
much more aggressive
and in your face.

00:35:34.920 --> 00:35:37.700
In the 1910s, what
we get is something

00:35:37.700 --> 00:35:39.680
that in some ways is
more attractive.

00:35:39.680 --> 00:35:43.980 position:56%
It's less violent use of foregrounds
where the characters are cut off

00:35:43.980 --> 00:35:47.650
at the waist or the hips or the
crotch or the knee or whatever

00:35:47.650 --> 00:35:50.390
to give a more fuller
sense, more air around them.

00:35:50.390 --> 00:35:53.030
But if you have more air around
them, you also have more room

00:35:53.030 --> 00:35:57.080
to play that little chess game of
choreography of the other figures.

00:35:57.080 --> 00:35:59.890
So let me just run a couple passes
through here, once that I saw here.

00:35:59.890 --> 00:36:02.280
I was lucky enough to see
over in the Madison building.

00:36:02.280 --> 00:36:05.760
Take "The Case of Becky" from
1915, a very interesting movie

00:36:05.760 --> 00:36:08.950
about a woman with a split
personality induced by hypnosis,

00:36:08.950 --> 00:36:11.830
kind of a schizophrenic case.

00:36:11.830 --> 00:36:17.860
She comes to get a job at this
dry good store and the camera

00:36:17.860 --> 00:36:21.560
as you see is cut off around the
knee or by the calf and the--

00:36:21.560 --> 00:36:25.270 position:56%
what we get are three figures, the
supervisor then the women supervisor

00:36:25.270 --> 00:36:27.420
and Becky and a man
in the background.

00:36:27.420 --> 00:36:28.920
And so we have depth already.

00:36:28.920 --> 00:36:31.790
In this case, it's
a little exceptional

00:36:31.790 --> 00:36:36.720 position:56%
because the camera budges a little,
it swivels a bit, it pans as we say.

00:36:36.720 --> 00:36:41.540
Because as the woman supervisor
takes her back behind the counter,

00:36:41.540 --> 00:36:44.340
this is kind of an audition to
see how she does with customers,

00:36:44.340 --> 00:36:47.870
the camera nudges itself over a
little bit but still keeps the guy

00:36:47.870 --> 00:36:49.170
in the background for us.

00:36:49.170 --> 00:36:50.470
You still get that rich depth.

00:36:50.470 --> 00:36:53.380
But what they did that's
rather daring, I think,

00:36:53.380 --> 00:36:56.350
is they don't follow the way
a modern filmmaker would,

00:36:56.350 --> 00:36:59.000
the people as they walk all the
way to the edge of the counter,

00:36:59.000 --> 00:37:02.370
the clerk and Becky,
they hold on the guy.

00:37:02.370 --> 00:37:05.040
They let-- He lets the
others go off screen

00:37:05.040 --> 00:37:08.320
in a way no theatre director
would ever let them go off stage

00:37:08.320 --> 00:37:10.560
and lets us-- there's'
really nothing else much

00:37:10.560 --> 00:37:12.480
to look at except that guy.

00:37:12.480 --> 00:37:15.700
So his reaction is
very salient for us.

00:37:15.700 --> 00:37:18.250
And indeed, as Becky comes
up and she looks at him,

00:37:18.250 --> 00:37:21.910
his reaction changes
and changes again.

00:37:21.910 --> 00:37:25.460
And you get a sense of the
rapacious interest on his part.

00:37:25.460 --> 00:37:28.920 position:56%
And by the end, when Becky has dealt
with the customer and turned away,

00:37:28.920 --> 00:37:32.710
you can tell he's kind of sizing
her up as a possible girlfriend

00:37:32.710 --> 00:37:36.820
without a close-up, no cuts,
just a little bump of the camera,

00:37:36.820 --> 00:37:41.170 position:56%
and gave us just that moment to look
at him and be aware that he is going

00:37:41.170 --> 00:37:44.000
to be important in this
interaction that's coming up.

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:46.980
So that flow that I'm talking
about substitutes for the--

00:37:46.980 --> 00:37:49.730
a percussive break that
you get with editing,

00:37:49.730 --> 00:37:52.770
and is in many ways no
less effective I think.

00:37:52.770 --> 00:37:56.370
Let me show some tactics
in this strategy.

00:37:56.370 --> 00:37:58.990
"The Circus Man", I read a
little blog entry about this,

00:37:58.990 --> 00:38:00.950
so you can look at it
online if you want.

00:38:00.950 --> 00:38:02.650
Here's a nice simple
example, I think.

00:38:02.650 --> 00:38:04.970 position:56%
The young man is uprighting the guys

00:38:04.970 --> 00:38:08.930
who sent this woman's husband
to jail for some years.

00:38:08.930 --> 00:38:11.000
And he's giving him
a piece of his mind.

00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:14.130
Whenever you see a door in tableau
films, keep your eye on the door,

