commercial cinema,

00:50:54.530 --> 00:50:58.340
because Hou Hsia-hsien is not
making mainstream films even

00:50:58.340 --> 00:51:01.250
to this day, I suppose.

00:51:01.250 --> 00:51:05.380
Finally, I want to say
some things about why.

00:51:05.380 --> 00:51:08.970
Why did the editing
approach gain supremacy?

00:51:08.970 --> 00:51:11.310
There are several possibilities and
we can talk about them if you want,

00:51:11.310 --> 00:51:14.760
but the one I think is most
compelling, at least as a major

00:51:14.760 --> 00:51:18.180
if not the only cause, you know,
the conditions of post-production

00:51:18.180 --> 00:51:20.670
and particularly production in
the American cinema at the time.

00:51:20.670 --> 00:51:23.080
Remember I mentioned this
explosion of filmmaking

00:51:23.080 --> 00:51:26.350
because there's an immense
popularity of the medium.

00:51:26.350 --> 00:51:30.810
They way you shoot a tableau is
really dependent on the director.

00:51:30.810 --> 00:51:33.430
The director is the
conductor of the orchestra.

00:51:33.430 --> 00:51:36.200
The director is shouting out--
Remember, this is a silent cinema

00:51:36.200 --> 00:51:38.400
and directors have megaphones.

00:51:38.400 --> 00:51:42.130
The director is shouting
out, move, pause,

00:51:42.130 --> 00:51:44.890
step behind the table,
pause, and so on.

00:51:44.890 --> 00:51:48.170
In fact, you can argue in fact
the bump that we get with editing,

00:51:48.170 --> 00:51:54.340
the little sense of a bump in a
cuts is kind of matched by poise--

00:51:54.340 --> 00:51:58.580
a position, freezing into place,
pausing in tableau cinema.

00:51:58.580 --> 00:52:00.690
So the rhythm of the
scene is partly dependent

00:52:00.690 --> 00:52:03.090
on people halting and
just not moving.

00:52:03.090 --> 00:52:05.670
The director commands
that because that's

00:52:05.670 --> 00:52:07.590
where the focus of
attention has to be.

00:52:07.590 --> 00:52:10.290
So the director is really king

00:52:10.290 --> 00:52:12.360
and controls the moment-by-moment
recording

00:52:12.360 --> 00:52:14.010
of the thing on the camera.

00:52:14.010 --> 00:52:18.540 position:56%
But the problem with that for a mass
market film industry is you can't

00:52:18.540 --> 00:52:20.870
really change much
in post-production.

00:52:20.870 --> 00:52:23.200
You don't have close-ups to cut to.

00:52:23.200 --> 00:52:25.100
You don't have anything
but this one long ribbon

00:52:25.100 --> 00:52:26.410
of film that's one long scene.

00:52:26.410 --> 00:52:29.800
You can interrupt it with
titles, and maybe if you want

00:52:29.800 --> 00:52:32.280
to take a few things out a
little bit, but it's very hard

00:52:32.280 --> 00:52:34.690
to alter those shots
in post-production,

00:52:34.690 --> 00:52:37.830
those long take tableau shots.

00:52:37.830 --> 00:52:40.730
So you see here as an example of
it, this is an earlier film studio.

00:52:40.730 --> 00:52:43.190
This is about 1907 or 8 I suppose.

00:52:43.190 --> 00:52:45.570
But you can see, the directors
are all lining up there,

00:52:45.570 --> 00:52:48.110
the cameras are all lined up,
several settings lined up side

00:52:48.110 --> 00:52:50.330
by side, because they're
filming side by side.

00:52:50.330 --> 00:52:52.380
And the directors are
really calling the shots,

00:52:52.380 --> 00:52:55.410
well I should say, the shot.

00:52:55.410 --> 00:52:59.200
But with editing, there
are two strong advantages.

00:52:59.200 --> 00:53:02.270
One-- For a mass market
industry, one is you can plan

00:53:02.270 --> 00:53:04.090 position:56%
out all the shots in pre-production.

00:53:04.090 --> 00:53:07.760 position:56%
Today, we have storyboards,
animated storyboards done digitally,

00:53:07.760 --> 00:53:10.410
but you can map out every
shot in advance if you want.

00:53:10.410 --> 00:53:12.040
You can make a shot
list, you can change it,

00:53:12.040 --> 00:53:14.330
you can make the whole
movie in your head on paper

00:53:14.330 --> 00:53:18.030
or on the screen before
you expose any film.

00:53:18.030 --> 00:53:21.370
Also, producers like the
possibility of editing,

00:53:21.370 --> 00:53:23.530
because you can change things.

00:53:23.530 --> 00:53:26.670
If a scene seems to be too slow,
you have something to cut away to.

00:53:26.670 --> 00:53:29.480
The producer always
says, "I need coverage.

00:53:29.480 --> 00:53:33.340 position:56%
Show me different positions of the
camera, different parts of the scene

00:53:33.340 --> 00:53:34.640
so I can pick up the pace,

00:53:34.640 --> 00:53:36.490
I can emphasize a performance
thing I like.

00:53:36.490 --> 00:53:40.180
I can cut out this actor
who is too mean," and so on.

00:53:40.180 --> 00:53:44.750 position:56%
That means the director is no longer
in the driver's seat scene by scene

00:53:44.750 --> 00:53:47.850
and the film can be controlled by
many other hands, the producer,

00:53:47.850 --> 00:53:51.070
the editor, people
further down the line.

00:53:51.070 --> 00:53:54.370
I'll show you an image from--
This is from an exchange,

00:53:54.370 --> 00:53:56.550
a film exchange, not a
film production company.

00:53:56.550 --> 00:54:00.500
Typically, when films arrive, you
know, in a city or really a center

00:54:00.500 --> 00:54:04.460
of distribution, people usually
women would be assembling them

00:54:04.460 --> 00:54:07.120
for distribution to
the actual theaters,

00:54:07.120 --> 00:54:09.380
and they're checking the film, in
this case, probably they're cutting

00:54:09.380 --> 00:54:13.030
in some titles, possibly tinting
the film, doing various things.

00:54:13.030 --> 00:54:16.480
The point is that once you've
got cuts, you can change things

00:54:16.480 --> 00:54:18.080
around in many, many ways.

00:54:18.080 --> 00:54:19.650
You could if you were
one of women working

00:54:19.650 --> 00:54:21.710
in this exchange actually
cut out things

00:54:21.710 --> 00:54:23.400
that local sensors
didn't want to see.

00:54:23.400 --> 00:54:26.020
You can simply take them out.

00:54:26.020 --> 00:54:28.160
In Chicago, maybe they
don't a play it.

00:54:28.160 --> 00:54:29.950
But in Cleveland, you could see it.

00:54:29.950 --> 00:54:33.410
So all those kinds of manipulations
are much more usually done

00:54:33.410 --> 00:54:35.530
with editing.

00:54:35.530 --> 00:54:38.650
So, I would argue that among
the prime causal reasons

00:54:38.650 --> 00:54:41.930
for the push towards editing
is the need for controlled,

00:54:41.930 --> 00:54:45.000
predictable mass production.

00:54:45.000 --> 00:54:50.320
If the tableau is the
friend of the directors,

00:54:50.320 --> 00:54:52.810
let's say editing is the
invention of producers.

00:54:52.810 --> 00:54:57.690
I'll give you a quick example
of what that look likes

00:54:57.690 --> 00:54:59.720
when the producer is
in the driver's seat

00:54:59.720 --> 00:55:03.360
and you get the layout
of shots scene by scene.

00:55:03.360 --> 00:55:07.100
This is a 1917 film now lost I
believe called "Love or Justice",

00:55:07.100 --> 00:55:10.400
but you can see very clearly,
at Nan's table, we have scene 5.

00:55:10.400 --> 00:55:12.220
They called shots scenes then.

00:55:12.220 --> 00:55:15.380
At Nan's table, Bill comes to the
table, moves around to Nan's side,

00:55:15.380 --> 00:55:18.610
seems to be carefully-- everything
is mapped out for the performer.

00:55:18.610 --> 00:55:22.750
Nan listens a moment then looks
off toward the other table.

00:55:22.750 --> 00:55:24.340
That's at scene 5.

00:55:24.340 --> 00:55:27.130
And the OK scribbled through
it means we made the shoot,

00:55:27.130 --> 00:55:29.150
we did what we were supposed to do.

00:55:29.150 --> 00:55:33.110
Then, scene 6, flash
close shot on Jack Dunn,

00:55:33.110 --> 00:55:35.330
close shot on Jack allowing
waiter's hands to come in.

00:55:35.330 --> 00:55:38.360
Even specifying the shot scale,
only see the waiter's hands,

00:55:38.360 --> 00:55:41.250
don't see the waiter, and place
the sandwich and the drink.

00:55:41.250 --> 00:55:42.600
He stares at them moodily.

00:55:42.600 --> 00:55:44.400
Again, OK, we made the shot.

00:55:44.400 --> 00:55:46.300
Above it though is
something interesting.

00:55:46.300 --> 00:55:51.610
Before scene 5, someone scribbled
in 4A, long shot, 4B, close-up boy.

00:55:51.610 --> 00:55:54.170
That was done on the set.

00:55:54.170 --> 00:55:58.520
But please not that now, the script
becomes a record of the production.

00:55:58.520 --> 00:56:01.580
We now know that the director
or somebody said, "Look,

00:56:01.580 --> 00:56:03.430
we better have a couple
more shoots here",

00:56:03.430 --> 00:56:05.860
maybe to give more playing
time or maybe it's to clear

00:56:05.860 --> 00:56:07.770
up where this action
is taking place.

00:56:07.770 --> 00:56:11.840
OK, the script girl, that's what
she was called, wrote in 4A,

00:56:11.840 --> 00:56:15.080
that's not 5 but there was a 4
before that that we don't we see.

00:56:15.080 --> 00:56:19.810
This is 4A, a different shot , a
long shoot and 4B, the close-up.

00:56:19.810 --> 00:56:22.310
And those are X'ed out
as having been completed.

00:56:22.310 --> 00:56:25.470
So, the script is controlling
not just production

00:56:25.470 --> 00:56:27.580
in the front office
from the distance.

00:56:27.580 --> 00:56:30.760
Moment by moment in the filming,
you're fitting what you do

00:56:30.760 --> 00:56:35.060
into the script, i.e. into the
shots as they're punching along.

00:56:35.060 --> 00:56:40.240
I want to thank everyone
