00:57:27.070 --> 00:57:30.010 position:56%
How do you want to handle questions?

00:57:30.010 --> 00:57:31.420
You want me to take them or
do you want to take them?

00:57:31.420 --> 00:57:32.720
&gt;&gt; Daniele Turello:
You can take them

00:57:32.720 --> 00:57:34.020
and there's a mic roaming around.

00:57:34.020 --> 00:57:35.320
&gt;&gt; David Bordwell: OK.

00:57:35.320 --> 00:57:36.620
There's a roaming mic.

00:57:36.620 --> 00:57:37.920
Yes, please?

00:57:37.920 --> 00:57:39.220
Hi.

00:57:39.220 --> 00:57:42.710
&gt;&gt; Hi. I'm unsure about this but
is basically montage was developed

00:57:42.710 --> 00:57:46.610
by Kuleshov and Eisenstein
on the '20s or was it the--

00:57:46.610 --> 00:57:54.240
and didn't Eisenstein
commend D.W. Griffith for--

00:57:54.240 --> 00:58:00.720
So, those techniques
of editing really sort

00:58:00.720 --> 00:58:02.250
of were developed very early.

00:58:02.250 --> 00:58:05.440
I mean, Griffith didn't himself
invent them, he just put--

00:58:05.440 --> 00:58:06.740
&gt;&gt; David Bordwell: No, he didn't.

00:58:06.740 --> 00:58:08.040
&gt;&gt; -- got them in one package.

00:58:08.040 --> 00:58:12.930
But now this montage itself was
just this hyperkinetic form editing

00:58:12.930 --> 00:58:14.440
in vague meaning.

00:58:14.440 --> 00:58:17.320
How does this film spit into
what you've been saying?

00:58:17.320 --> 00:58:18.760
&gt;&gt; David Bordwell: It's
a very good question.

00:58:18.760 --> 00:58:21.840
These films were seen
in-- the films or the kind

00:58:21.840 --> 00:58:24.010
of films I'm describing
were seen in many parts

00:58:24.010 --> 00:58:25.960
of the world during the teens.

00:58:25.960 --> 00:58:30.470
And they eventually made their way
to Russia and were taken up the

00:58:30.470 --> 00:58:31.950
by the younger generation
filmmakers,

00:58:31.950 --> 00:58:34.780
the one you mentioned
Kuleshov, Eisenstein, Pudovkin,

00:58:34.780 --> 00:58:37.230
they saw them as--
it is perfect example

00:58:37.230 --> 00:58:38.530
of what I've been describing.

00:58:38.530 --> 00:58:40.920
They saw them as the
coolest new thing.

00:58:40.920 --> 00:58:44.440
The tableau ruled Czarist cinema.

00:58:44.440 --> 00:58:46.870
But once the revolution took place,

00:58:46.870 --> 00:58:49.810
the young directors decided
this is the way to go,

00:58:49.810 --> 00:58:51.850 position:56%
just as Lenin wanted electrification

00:58:51.850 --> 00:58:53.750
and power plants and
things like that.

00:58:53.750 --> 00:58:56.530
They were able hitch their
wagon to that star and say,

00:58:56.530 --> 00:58:58.010
look, we have to modernize.

00:58:58.010 --> 00:59:01.320
And the Americans are the source
of this kind of modernity.

00:59:01.320 --> 00:59:04.130
So, we will take what
the Americans did.

00:59:04.130 --> 00:59:06.870
And in fact, you know,
we call it Soviet montage

00:59:06.870 --> 00:59:10.420
but the Russians called
it American montage,

00:59:10.420 --> 00:59:13.750
because they saw themselves very
much as influenced by this trend.

00:59:13.750 --> 00:59:16.220
And as you say, they
pushed it farther.

00:59:16.220 --> 00:59:19.580
They realized that there are
more possibilities in montage

00:59:19.580 --> 00:59:21.390
than the Americans have realized.

00:59:21.390 --> 00:59:23.800 position:56%
You can make shots very, very short.

00:59:23.800 --> 00:59:26.640
You can make abstract points with
shots and that's kind of an error

00:59:26.640 --> 00:59:29.340
in some of the teen's films.

00:59:29.340 --> 00:59:32.770
There's moralizing or allegorical
films that use sort of abstract--

00:59:32.770 --> 00:59:35.020
use editing for abstractions.

00:59:35.020 --> 00:59:37.230
But of course, people like
Eisenstein went much farther

00:59:37.230 --> 00:59:39.900
with that, it sends us in
"Strike" and "October".

00:59:39.900 --> 00:59:44.660
So, they push the American
continuity system to a kind

00:59:44.660 --> 00:59:47.360
of crisis, I would argue,
and create a kind of cinema

00:59:47.360 --> 00:59:51.630
of discontinuity that's built
on the continuity system.

00:59:51.630 --> 00:59:53.600
They keep pushing and
pushing in various ways.

00:59:53.600 --> 00:59:56.690 position:56%
Each one of them has their own
style, those major soviet directors.

00:59:56.690 --> 00:59:57.990
But you're right.

00:59:57.990 --> 01:00:02.940
This is where it becomes
a new kind of cinema.

01:00:02.940 --> 01:00:05.530
The other point you raised about
Eisenstein is dead right also.

01:00:05.530 --> 01:00:07.470
But that's in a period
of Eisenstein's work

01:00:07.470 --> 01:00:10.040
where he's looking--
he's less of a radical.

01:00:10.040 --> 01:00:11.780
He writes that essay, "Later".

01:00:11.780 --> 01:00:14.630
And he's less of radical
than he was in his 20s.

01:00:14.630 --> 01:00:18.430
And he's looking for classical
sources for what cinema has done.

01:00:18.430 --> 01:00:21.070
He's trying to give cinema
a distinguished lineage

01:00:21.070 --> 01:00:22.500
in the history of the arts.

01:00:22.500 --> 01:00:25.680
So just as he'll say, "Well,
here's a framing here from Pudovkin

01:00:25.680 --> 01:00:28.060
that reminds you of
Del Greco," and so on.

01:00:28.060 --> 01:00:32.000 position:56%
He'll try to give a kind of
intellectual authority of legitimacy

01:00:32.000 --> 01:00:36.530 position:56%
to what cinema has been as in cinema
is the next logical step for him

01:00:36.530 --> 01:00:38.630
in the evolution of
the arts in general.

01:00:38.630 --> 01:00:42.440
So, naturally, what the 19th
century novelists were doing,

01:00:42.440 --> 01:00:46.130
Griffith with his crosscutting
in "The Cricket

01:00:46.130 --> 01:00:48.530 position:56%
on the Hearth" is what Griffith did.

01:00:48.530 --> 01:00:50.640
Griffith did it too
but he did it on film.

01:00:50.640 --> 01:00:54.360
He swallowed up another art
form and pushed it farther.

01:00:54.360 --> 01:00:57.530
So that's a particular position
Eisenstein wants to push.

01:00:57.530 --> 01:00:58.830
But you're right.

01:00:58.830 --> 01:01:01.530
This American cinema is
very, very influential

01:01:01.530 --> 01:01:05.620
on the Soviet montage people.

01:01:05.620 --> 01:01:07.000
Yes, Andrei, please?

01:01:07.000 --> 01:01:09.860
&gt;&gt; Doctor Bordwell, thank
you for this lecture.

01:01:09.860 --> 01:01:12.820
A couple of years ago, I
was watching George Clooney

01:01:12.820 --> 01:01:14.730
on "Inside the Actors Studio".

01:01:14.730 --> 01:01:16.320
And James Lipton asked him,

01:01:16.320 --> 01:01:18.840
what's the most important
aspect of directing?

01:01:18.840 --> 01:01:20.360
And Mr. Clooney didn't hesitate.

01:01:20.360 --> 01:01:22.880
He said, point of view.

01:01:22.880 --> 01:01:27.620
And I thought about that
quite a bit since then.

01:01:27.620 --> 01:01:34.970 position:56%
So, point of view not just in the
sense of emphasis but identification

01:01:34.970 --> 01:01:38.610
to get the audience to identify
with a particular character.

01:01:38.610 --> 01:01:42.500
So my question is, for you, in
this period that you've focused

01:01:42.500 --> 01:01:46.930
on for study, do you --
did you see, shall we say,

01:01:46.930 --> 01:01:51.370
instances of the beginning of some
of these techniques for the purpose

01:01:51.370 --> 01:01:53.640
of enhancing identification?

01:01:53.640 --> 01:01:54.940
&gt;&gt; David Bordwell: Mm-hmm.

01:01:54.940 --> 01:01:57.000
Well, I think there's two or
three ways to deal with it, yes.

01:01:57.000 --> 01:02:00.130
One is we could identify
with figures

01:02:00.130 --> 01:02:01.900
that we see simply
because we see them.

01:02:01.900 --> 01:02:04.590
We're very responsive
to faces and postures

01:02:04.590 --> 01:02:08.010 position:56%
and those can enhance identification
and I think that's the actor's craft

01:02:08.010 --> 01:02:10.730
in both of the trends that
I'm trying to analyze.

01:02:10.730 --> 01:02:13.350
You get a powerful sense
of empathy for instance

01:02:13.350 --> 01:02:15.230
in that Lois Weber example.

01:02:15.230 --> 01:02:18.150
But a more broader sense, I think,

01:02:18.150 --> 01:02:21.910
what you're asking is even more
interesting and that is one

01:02:21.910 --> 01:02:25.190
of those faults of the
tableau cinema, you can argue,

01:02:25.190 --> 01:02:28.100
is that it doesn't allow for
that kind of optical point

01:02:28.100 --> 01:02:29.880
of view, the editing does.

01:02:29.880 --> 01:02:32.670
You can't really put the
camera in the shoes or the eyes

01:02:32.670 --> 01:02:35.350
of another character
in the tableau cinema.

01:02:35.350 --> 01:02:37.370
Everything is based on
a kind of omniscience.

01:02:37.370 --> 01:02:41.040 position:56%
We see everything we need to see and
then maybe it's not like the kind

01:02:41.040 --> 01:02:42.770 position:56%
of omniscience on the theatre stage.

01:02:42.770 --> 01:02:45.600
Nevertheless, there's a sense
of hovering over the action

01:02:45.600 --> 01:02:47.700
and we may be aware of things
that the actors aren't,

01:02:47.700 --> 01:02:50.310
often because they're standing
with their backs to each other.

01:02:50.310 --> 01:02:55.360
So, there is a harder hill to climb
to get that kind of say, let's say,

01:02:55.360 --> 01:02:59.240
Hitchcockean shot of person
looking, shot of what they see,

01:02:59.240 --> 01:03:01.520
closer shot of looking,
closer of what they see,

01:03:01.520 --> 01:03:04.540
that kind of intensification
on point of view is harder

01:03:04.540 --> 01:03:05.840
to achieve in the tableau cinema.

01:03:05.840 --> 01:03:10.360
And if that's one of the routes
we can take to an identification,

01:03:10.360 --> 01:03:13.830
then that's, you know, one of
those things that it is a deficit

01:03:13.830 --> 01:03:16.680
of the tableau cinema and probably
help the advance of editing.

01:03:16.680 --> 01:03:20.770
So it comes in-- POV shots come in
very early in the history cinema,

01:03:20.770 --> 01:03:22.170
then they drop out for a while.

01:03:22.170 --> 01:03:24.770
They're usually just stunts or
what Tom Gunning calls attractions.

01:03:24.770 --> 01:03:27.540
Later, they get integrated
into stories

01:03:27.540 --> 01:03:29.340
and editing is the
way it's done, yeah.

01:03:29.340 --> 01:03:33.150
So that mention of point of view
is really, I think, you know,

01:03:33.150 --> 01:03:35.820
there's a bias in editing
towards that.

01:03:35.820 --> 01:03:38.570
But of course, you know,
empathy takes many forms

01:03:38.570 --> 01:03:41.950
and you can find lots of cases
where extreme long shots,

01:03:41.950 --> 01:03:44.850
people are watching in the
extreme long shot and crying.

01:03:44.850 --> 01:03:46.150
You think of the end of say,

01:03:46.150 --> 01:03:47.460
Kiarostami's "Through
the Olive Trees",

01:03:47.460 --> 01:03:48.970
I don't know if you've
seen that film.

01:03:48.970 --> 01:03:52.420
Well, it's prolonged long
shot, it must be a mile away.

01:03:52.420 --> 01:03:54.270
I don't know how far away it is.

01:03:54.270 --> 01:03:56.440
And everybody is riveted,

01:03:56.440 --> 01:03:59.360
and feeling for the
character who's in that shot.

01:03:59.360 --> 01:04:02.190
So, there are many avenues,
I think, towards that kind

01:04:02.190 --> 01:04:04.420
of identification you're
talking about.

01:04:04.420 --> 01:04:08.520
But certainly, it can be bought
pretty cheaply through cutting.

01:04:08.520 --> 01:04:09.860
Yes, please?

01:04:09.860 --> 01:04:14.940
&gt;&gt; When you said the tableau system
survived in Germany till 1919-1920,

01:04:14.940 --> 01:04:17.300
then began running "The
Cabinet of Dr. Caligari"--

01:04:17.300 --> 01:04:18.600
&gt;&gt; David Bordwell: Yes.

01:04:18.600 --> 01:04:22.020
&gt;&gt; And that seems like tableau film
because they certainly want you

01:04:22.020 --> 01:04:24.360
to make use of those sets.

01:04:24.360 --> 01:04:28.390
But it also incorporates
these shot cuts of Cesare.

01:04:28.390 --> 01:04:31.020
So, I wonder how you
would categorize Caligari?

01:04:31.020 --> 01:04:32.320
&gt;&gt; David Bordwell: Yup, yup.

01:04:32.320 --> 01:04:33.620
That's a great point.

01:04:33.620 --> 01:04:35.900
I didn't have time to elaborate
on this but you're quite right.

01:04:35.900 --> 01:04:39.550
What happens in the teens in
both America and Europe is

01:04:39.550 --> 01:04:44.070
that directors start to sort of go
halfway or partway towards editing,

01:04:44.070 --> 01:04:48.050
the tableau directors through
a simple axial cut in and out.

01:04:48.050 --> 01:04:51.120 position:56%
So for instances, they understand
you're supposed to emphasize things,

01:04:51.120 --> 01:04:53.070
but instead of building the
scene out of cuts the way

01:04:53.070 --> 01:04:56.600
in an American would, you simply
have the tableau, it goes on and on

01:04:56.600 --> 01:04:59.730
and on, and then boom,
an enlargement of a face,

01:04:59.730 --> 01:05:01.450
and then boom, back into tableau.

01:05:01.450 --> 01:05:04.510
This might thought of as like
a proto-continuity system.

01:05:04.510 --> 01:05:06.410
You're always in the master shot.

01:05:06.410 --> 01:05:09.320
And that is what you get in
Caligari for the most part.

01:05:09.320 --> 01:05:13.470
You get the enlargements of
either Cesare or the doctor,

01:05:13.470 --> 01:05:17.750
often in an iris, a kind
of circular-shaped mask

01:05:17.750 --> 01:05:22.590
which emphasized that, a kind of a
little italicization of that Roman.

01:05:22.590 --> 01:05:25.800 position:56%
But Caligari also uses
crosscutting, a lot of crosscutting.

01:05:25.800 --> 01:05:28.940
And that shows by that
point, American cinema's--

01:05:28.940 --> 01:05:30.700
that's seen everywhere now.

01:05:30.700 --> 01:05:32.000
The people adapt that.

01:05:32.000 --> 01:05:34.820
Even Fayyad who is very
conservative adopts crosscutting.

01:05:34.820 --> 01:05:37.360
So, it's a partial
concession, I would say,

01:05:37.360 --> 01:05:39.030
to the American system, Caligari.

01:05:39.030 --> 01:05:40.830
But Caligari, you're
certainly right.

01:05:40.830 --> 01:05:44.600
The absorption of the
sets and the emphasis

01:05:44.600 --> 01:05:50.120
on a quasi-dance-like performance
style in both Cesare of course,

01:05:50.120 --> 01:05:51.840
but in the others, is there too.

01:05:51.840 --> 01:05:55.990
So, there a lot of compromises
in that tableau tradition,

01:05:55.990 --> 01:05:59.140
particularly after the
Americans would get out there.

01:05:59.140 --> 01:06:03.100
Caligari was made when they could
see American films as is the film

01:06:03.100 --> 01:06:05.220
that I mentioned, "Nerven"
by Reinert,

01:06:05.220 --> 01:06:07.320
which was made the
same year as Caligari.

01:06:07.320 --> 01:06:09.350
And in my view, if you
can see it, it's on DVD.

01:06:09.350 --> 01:06:11.360
You can get on online.

01:06:11.360 --> 01:06:13.610
"Nerven" would be as
famous as Caligari

01:06:13.610 --> 01:06:17.070
if people had seen it outside
Germany but it wasn't well-known,

01:06:17.070 --> 01:06:19.500
it wasn't preserved in
archives, and not so--

01:06:19.500 --> 01:06:22.680
it wasn't as publicized in
such a self-congratulatory way

01:06:22.680 --> 01:06:23.980
as Caligari was.

01:06:23.980 --> 01:06:25.840
But in general, your point is
quite right, that there are--

01:06:25.840 --> 01:06:29.090
these films have sort of
partial use of each tradition

01:06:29.090 --> 01:06:32.540
and sometimes it's just the matter
of using one more than another.

01:06:32.540 --> 01:06:37.780
Yup? This side.

01:06:39.230 --> 01:06:46.570
&gt;&gt; The French Criticoms wrote this
in, wrote about the superiority

01:06:46.570 --> 01:06:51.310
of the deep focus or the
deep sets and it seems

01:06:51.310 --> 01:06:53.800
to have something in
common with tableau.

01:06:53.800 --> 01:06:58.640
It's more, I think-- he was saying
the audience had more freedom,

01:06:58.640 --> 01:07:04.360
you're not directed every single--
And also, there's more ability to--

01:07:04.360 --> 01:07:07.450
it's more of a contemplative--

01:07:07.450 --> 01:07:08.750
&gt;&gt; David Bordwell: Yes.

01:07:08.750 --> 01:07:10.070 position:56%
&gt;&gt; -- cinema than the editing style.

01:07:10.070 --> 01:07:11.380
Do you agree with that?

01:07:11.380 --> 01:07:13.540
Do you see a similarity
with tableau?

01:07:13.540 --> 01:07:15.050
How do you relate that?

01:07:15.050 --> 01:07:16.410
&gt;&gt; David Bordwell: I
really am listening.

01:07:16.410 --> 01:07:23.870
I'm just trying to find an image,
I think, that will help us.

01:07:23.870 --> 01:07:29.500 position:56%
Yeah. What I would say is this, that
Bezen [assumed spelling] generalizes

01:07:29.500 --> 01:07:32.820
from the Welles and Wyler
films he's been seeing.

01:07:32.820 --> 01:07:35.450
And he wants to know
where they come from.

01:07:35.450 --> 01:07:38.380 position:56%
And I guess the complicated argument
about that deep focus style,

01:07:38.380 --> 01:07:40.920 position:56%
if I can show you this, there, that.

01:07:40.920 --> 01:07:44.470
His argument as I understand,
it goes like this.

01:07:44.470 --> 01:07:47.730
Back in the day, there is what
he calls primitive deep focus,

01:07:47.730 --> 01:07:50.070
and that would include
the very earliest films,

01:07:50.070 --> 01:07:53.520
mostly those shot outdoors like the
Lumière films and things like that

01:07:53.520 --> 01:07:56.570
where you can see lots of space
in the background, cityscapes,

01:07:56.570 --> 01:07:57.870
people moving around, all that.

01:07:57.870 --> 01:08:00.850
You have primitive deep focus but
that's kind of given automatically

01:08:00.850 --> 01:08:03.570
by the camera, the nature
of lighting, and so on.

01:08:03.570 --> 01:08:06.060
And then, thing become very
hermetic in the studios,

01:08:06.060 --> 01:08:09.050
you're inside the studios
and cutting rules.

01:08:09.050 --> 01:08:12.350
And then, by the '30s,-- Bezen's,
this is a story Bezen tells.

01:08:12.350 --> 01:08:15.680
By the '30s, everybody knows how to
cut, and sound has been mastered,

01:08:15.680 --> 01:08:17.480
so we know how to cut
for sound cinema.

01:08:17.480 --> 01:08:20.140
So, there's a kind of
equilibrium reached throughout 1939

01:08:20.140 --> 01:08:22.940
where you can really use this
standard continuity system

01:08:22.940 --> 01:08:24.240
to say anything.

01:08:24.240 --> 01:08:25.540
You can tell a gangster film.

01:08:25.540 --> 01:08:26.840
You can tell a musical, whatever.

01:08:26.840 --> 01:08:31.650
What Welles and Wyler do is they
come to fulfill a kind of prophecy

01:08:31.650 --> 01:08:36.930
of synthesizing the primitive deep
focus and the cinema of editing.

01:08:36.930 --> 01:08:42.840
His argument is that shot like
this is a kind of compact diversion

01:08:42.840 --> 01:08:47.170
of a close-up, a medium
shot and a long shoot.

01:08:47.170 --> 01:08:51.510
It's as if Welles had figured out a
way to give us all the information

01:08:51.510 --> 01:08:56.780
that would normally be given in an
edited sequence in a single frame.

01:08:56.780 --> 01:08:58.080
He spaced them out almost--

01:08:58.080 --> 01:09:02.130
Bezen, you know, suggests it's like
an explode a diagram of a motor,

01:09:02.130 --> 01:09:04.690
you know, like all the pieces
are kind of hovering in space

01:09:04.690 --> 01:09:06.640
but it's within this one diagram.

01:09:06.640 --> 01:09:09.730
So his argument is the
primitive deep focus is absorbed

01:09:09.730 --> 01:09:15.010
but classicized or
continuitized in Welles and Wyler.

01:09:15.010 --> 01:09:17.990
So the version of deep focus
he has here is a synthesis

01:09:17.990 --> 01:09:20.710 position:56%
of the continuity, editing tradition

01:09:20.710 --> 01:09:22.540
and what he called
primitive deep focus.

01:09:22.540 --> 01:09:25.140
From my standpoint, he
can't be blamed for this

01:09:25.140 --> 01:09:27.610 position:56%
because people didn't see the films,
he didn't know about these films

01:09:27.610 --> 01:09:30.270
of the teens, the tableau
films of the teens,

01:09:30.270 --> 01:09:33.570
which are not primitive deep focus
in the way he's thinking of it,

01:09:33.570 --> 01:09:35.830
but also aren't editing either.

01:09:35.830 --> 01:09:38.280
So, to my sense, Bezen, you know,

01:09:38.280 --> 01:09:41.130
he saw what he could see
and he said what he can.

01:09:41.130 --> 01:09:42.960
But there's a sense in which

01:09:42.960 --> 01:09:46.980
that argument sees everything
is evolving towards this.

01:09:46.980 --> 01:09:48.560
He was a very much a
pretentious critic.

01:09:48.560 --> 01:09:51.580
He thought this is really kind
of the end of cinema style.

01:09:51.580 --> 01:09:52.880
There's no further to go than this.

01:09:52.880 --> 01:09:54.180
We can have color, yes.

01:09:54.180 --> 01:09:55.480
We can have 3D.

01:09:55.480 --> 01:09:56.780
You can have those things.

01:09:56.780 --> 01:09:58.740
But as far as style is concerned,
it's pretty much a dead end.

01:09:58.740 --> 01:10:00.040
We're finished.

01:10:00.040 --> 01:10:02.690
Welles and Wyler have given
us the perfect form of cinema.

01:10:02.690 --> 01:10:04.530
Editing is given to us in a way

01:10:04.530 --> 01:10:07.710
that it respects the
integrity of time and space.

01:10:07.710 --> 01:10:10.710
So the problem with editing
is it chops everything up.

01:10:10.710 --> 01:10:15.350 position:56%
Here, we get the world organized,
dynamized, focused for our attention

01:10:15.350 --> 01:10:17.030
without doing those things.

01:10:17.030 --> 01:10:20.790
And it's part of his theory about
what is really artistic cinema,

01:10:20.790 --> 01:10:23.170
the value of certain
kinds of filmmaking.

01:10:23.170 --> 01:10:25.530
That's my take on it anyway.

